\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Overview of end-to-end differentiable constellation optimization. \textbf  {Top:} Starting from a poorly-configured constellation with randomly spaced orbital planes and satellites, gradient optimization through the differentiable pipeline recovers a well-spaced constellation optimized for both coverage and revisit for a set of ground points. \textbf  {Bottom:} Orbital parameters $\boldsymbol  {\theta }_i$ are propagated through a differentiable orbit propagator and evaluated against a set of ground targets $\mathbf  {g}_j$ to produce relaxed coverage and revisit metrics ($\tilde  {C}$, $\tilde  {\Delta }^{\max }$), which form a differentiable loss $\mathcal  {L}$. Gradients $\nabla _{\boldsymbol  {\theta }}\mathcal  {L}$ flow back to the orbital parameters via reverse-mode automatic differentiation (dashed).}}{2}{figure.caption.1}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig:pipeline}{{1}{2}{Overview of end-to-end differentiable constellation optimization. \textbf {Top:} Starting from a poorly-configured constellation with randomly spaced orbital planes and satellites, gradient optimization through the differentiable pipeline recovers a well-spaced constellation optimized for both coverage and revisit for a set of ground points. \textbf {Bottom:} Orbital parameters $\boldsymbol {\theta }_i$ are propagated through a differentiable orbit propagator and evaluated against a set of ground targets $\vect {g}_j$ to produce relaxed coverage and revisit metrics ($\tilde {C}$, $\tilde {\Delta }^{\max }$), which form a differentiable loss $\mathcal {L}$. Gradients $\nabla _{\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mathcal {L}$ flow back to the orbital parameters via reverse-mode automatic differentiation (dashed)}{figure.caption.1}{}}
